      • readBulkInData

        public int readBulkInData(byte[] data,
                          int ibFirst,
                          int cbToRead,
                          long msTimeout,
                          TimeWindow timeWindow)
                   throws java.lang.InterruptedException
        Attempt to read cbToRead bytes from the device, subject to a timeout
        Parameters:
        data - the buffer into which the data is to be placed, starting at the beginning
        cbToRead - the number of bytes to read
        msTimeout - the number of milliseconds to wait for the result
        timeWindow - optional place into which to record the timestamps that cover the duration of the read data
        Returns:
        the number of bytes read (zero means the timeout is reached w/o returning the data unless the number of bytes to read was itself zero) FT_Device.RC_DEVICE_CLOSED : the device was closed
        Throws:
        java.lang.InterruptedException

      • processEventChars

        public int processEventChars(boolean fRxChar,
                             short sEvents,
                             short slEvents)
                      throws java.lang.InterruptedException
        The original implementation of processEventChars used an in-process broadcast as notification mechanism. That required a whole new external library (implementing LocalBroadcastManager) which we'd very much not like to have to link in here. And since we presently don't need such a notification mechanism, we'll do without it for now. Recommendation: if we ever DO need such a thing, use a better mechanism :-).

        From the FTDI D2XX Programmer's Guide:

        "The least significant byte of the lpdwModemStatus value holds the modem status. On Windows and Windows CE, the line status is held in the second least significant byte of the lpdwModemStatus value.

        The modem status is bit-mapped as follows: Clear To Send (CTS) = 0x10, Data Set Ready (DSR) = 0x20, Ring Indicator (RI) = 0x40, Data Carrier Detect (DCD) = 0x80.

        The line status is bit-mapped as follows: Overrun Error (OE) = 0x02, Parity Error (PE) = 0x04, Framing Error (FE) = 0x08, Break Interrupt (BI) = 0x10."

        Throws:
        java.lang.InterruptedException
